rComments: Dr. Pressey is a very knowledgeable lecturer, she knows the material very well. The material covered by this class isn't easy, but super interesting. She answers emails and is available outside of class time to help you out if you need it!!

rComments: Absolutely the worst lecturer I've ever come across. Not only does Dr. Pressey skim through her slides, but it seems that she doesn't practice how to lecture. Often times she will say "I'm not sure if I'm explaining this right" or even brush off certain slides by saying "whatever". It's highly unprofessional and stressful for students. AVOID HER.

Dr. Pressey wasn't even that bad of a lecturer. Maybe she spoke a little too fast, but she usually went over the gist of the material in enough detail, or at least I thought so. You can tell she actually cares about the students: she provided extra videos on unclear topics and tried her best to reweigh the test for the benefit of everyone.

Dr. Pressey really enjoys neuroscience and knows the material well, but teaches like the students have already learned the material. Her slides are missing a lot of key info, so there's a lot to fill in class (which is fine), but she'll talk quickly, skimming over key concepts and proteins (which are nowhere in the slides), as if we already know.
Speaks way too fast, needs to slow down explaining concepts/ take some breaths. She should listen to her own recordings before she writes the test.
She should probably head upstairs to OISE and learn how to teach students. She seems nice tho.

Here's the gist: has a very solid neuroscience background, highly approachable, promotes asking questions, is very clear in explanations, gives hints about tests, and overall decent lecturer BUT speaks WAY too fast, does not repeat key concepts, tends to read off slides, and does not specify what we DON'T need to know (lots of extra/random stuff)
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Lecture heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass."]
